                      <div class="panel panel-default primary-card mb-40 faq-panel" id="editing-faq">   
                        <div class="panel-heading" style="padding: 5px 15px;" role="tab">
                          <h2 class="panel-title collapsed" role="button" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse-general-4" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapse-general-4" id="heading-general-4">
                            <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-down float-right faq-toggle-content"></span>
                            Why can people edit my posts? How does editing work?
                          </h2>
                        </div>
                        <div id="collapse-general-4" class="panel-collapse collapse" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="heading-general-4">
                          <div class="panel-body">
                            <p class='reg-p'>This site is a collaborative effort. If you see a problem or topic that needs improvement, click edit!<p>
                            <p class='reg-p'>We believe that the collective wisdom of users ensures the quality of posts. Editing is important for keeping problems and topics clear, grammatically correct and relevant.<p>
                            <h3>When to edit posts</h3>
                            <p class='reg-p'> Whenever you see a post that can be improved, it is ecouraged to edit it. Edits are expected to leave the post better than how you found it. Here are some reasons for edits: </p>
                            <ul>
                              <li class='reg-item'>To improve spelling, grammar or punctuation</li>
                              <li class='reg-item'>To clarify the meaning of the post. It is important not to change the intended meaning of the poster.</li>
                              <li class='reg-item'>To include important information that is found in the comments. Sometimes additional information or a clarification arises in the comments. It is better to keep all of the relevant information in one place.</li>
                              <li class='reg-item'>To correct a mistake or error made</li>
                              <li class='reg-item'>To add citations, links or resources</li>
                            </ul>
                            <h3>Who can edit posts?</h3>
                            <p class='reg-p'>Only trusted members of the community can edit posts. You need at least 2500 reputation points to edit problems and proofs, and at least 3000 reputation to edit topics. The creator of the post can always edit their own post, regardless of their reputation.</p>
                            <h3>What happens after I edit a post?</h3>
                            <p class='reg-p'>The post will update to show the latest editor as well as the original creator. All edits are saved and tracked in the posts version history. Each version will be viewable along with the editor in the post's log. Editing a post will bump it to the top of the feed.</p>
                            <h3>What if the edit was bad?</h3>
                            <p class='reg-p'>Common users can report edits. If the latest edit gets 5 or more reports then the latest version will be reverted to its previous version and the edit will disappear from the log. Trusted users with at least 5000 reputation, and original authors can rollback edits automatically.</p>
                          </div>
                        </div>
                      </div><!-- / .panel -->

                      <div class="panel panel-default primary-card mb-40 faq-panel">   
                        <div class="panel-heading" style="padding: 5px 15px;" role="tab">
                          <h2 class="panel-title collapsed" role="button" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse-general-5" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapse-general-5" id="heading-general-5">
                            <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-down float-right faq-toggle-content"></span>
                            What if I need more help?
                          </h2>
                        </div>
                        <div id="collapse-general-5" class="panel-collapse collapse" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="heading-general-5">
                          <div class="panel-body">
                            <p class='reg-p'>If you have a question, need more information, are experiencing an error, or want to report a security vulnerabilty, please <%= link_to "contact us directly", contact_path %>.</p>
                          </div>
                        </div>
                      </div><!-- / .panel -->
 
                      <div class="panel panel-default primary-card mb-40 faq-panel" id="create-new-topic-faq">   
                        <div class="panel-heading" style="padding: 5px 15px;" role="tab">
                          <h2 class="panel-title collapsed" role="button" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse-general-6" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapse-general-6" id="heading-general-6">
                            <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-down float-right faq-toggle-content"></span>
                            Creating Topics
                          </h2>
                        </div>
                        <div id="collapse-general-6" class="panel-collapse collapse" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="heading-general-6">
                          <div class="panel-body">
                            <p class='reg-p'>Trusted users with at least 3000 reputation can create new topics. You should only create a new topic when you are sure that your problem covers a new topic and no one else has asked about before. As a general rule, you should avoid creating new topics if possible.</p>
                            <h3>How do I create a new topic?</h3>
                            <p class='reg-p'>If you are a trusted member then a link to create a new topic will appear on your homepage sidebar. When creating the topic, bear in mind that topic names must not be longer than 35 characters, and can only use the following chacter set: <code>a-z</code>, <code>0-9</code>, <code>+</code>, <code>#</code>, <code>-</code>, <code>.</code>. You must provide a description of the topic as well.</p>
                            <h3>What happens after a new topic is created?</h3>
                            <p class='reg-p'>The new topic will now be available for all other users to use and follow. If they are not used by any questions in a 4 month period, the topic will be removed.</p>
                            <p class='reg-p'>Please create topics responsibly!</p>
                          </div>
                        </div>
                      </div><!-- / .panel -->

                      <div class="panel panel-default primary-card mb-40 faq-panel" id="post-deletion-faq">
                        <div class="panel-heading" style="padding: 5px 15px;" role="tab">
                          <h2 class="panel-title collapsed" role="button" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse-general-7" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapse-general-7" id="heading-general-7">
                            <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-down float-right faq-toggle-content"></span>
                            How Can a Post be Deleted?
                          </h2>
                        </div>
                        <div id="collapse-general-7" class="panel-collapse collapse" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="heading-general-7">
                          <div class="panel-body">

                            <h3>By a User:</h3>

                            <ul>
                              <li class='reg-item'><b>The author</b> can typically delete their own posts, except when: 
                                <ul>
                                  <li>the problem in question has any proofs with upvotes.</li>
                                  <li>the proof in question has upvotes (it doesn't matter if  the overall score is negative).</li>
                                </ul>
                              </li>
                              <li class='reg-item'><b>Moderators</b> can delete any posts instantly.</li>
                              <li class='reg-item'><b>Users with 15000 reputation or more</b> can vote to delete a post that is in the "review queue". 3 votes are needed for the post to be deleted.</li>
                            </ul>

                            <h3>By the System:</h3>

                            <ul>
                              <li class='reg-item'><b>Dead problem:</b> Problems that are over 60 days old, with a negative score and no proofs will automatically be deleted.</li>
                              <li class='reg-item'><b>Reported problems:</b> Problems that are over 30 days old, with 3 or more reports and no proofs will automatically be deleted.</li>
                              <li class='reg-item'><b>Spam or abusive posts</b> If a problem or proof receives 8 spam or offensive reports, they will be automatically deleted. The owner of the post will also receive -100 reputation points.
                              <li class='reg-item'><b>Bad comments:</b> Comments that have a voting score of -5 or less, or 3 or more reports with a score of 0 or less will automatically be deleted.</li>
                            </ul>

                            <h3>What is the Review Queue?</h3>
                            <p class='reg-p'>Posts in the review queue are automatically locked, and are reviewed thoroughly by moderators and users with <%= link_to "deletion priviliges", "#deletion-priv-faq", easing: "linear" %>. An effort is made to edit the post and to mark it as OK if it can be improved, otherwise they are deleted.</p>
                            <h3>How does a post get put in the Review Queue?</h3>
                            <ul>
                              <li class='reg-item'>A problem with a voting score of -6 is put in the queue.</li>
                              <li class='reg-item'>A proof with a voting score of -4 is put in the queue.</li>
                              <li class='reg-item'>Any post with 3 or more reports (that are not spam or offensive flag reports) is put in the queue.</li>
                            </ul>
                            <h3>What Happens After my Post has Been Taken out of the Review Queue?</h3>
                            <p class='reg-p'>If the post manages to get out of the review queue, the reports expire and its voting score stays the same. A secondary score will be kept from the moment it is taken out of the review queue, and if this score falls below a -3, it will automatically be deleted. If the post receives 3 or more reports after being released from the review queue, it will also be deleted.</p>
                          </div>
                        </div>
                      </div><!-- / .panel --> 
                    </div>
                    <div class="mt-20" id="reputation">
                      <h1 class="mb-20 reg-h1"> Reputation </h1>

                      <div class="panel panel-default primary-card mb-40 faq-panel">   
                        <div class="panel-heading" style="padding: 5px 15px;" role="tab">
                          <h2 class="panel-title collapsed" role="button" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse-reputation-1" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapse-reputation-1" id="heading-reputation-1">
                            <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-down float-right faq-toggle-content"></span>
                            What is reputation and how do I earn it?
                          </h2>
                        </div>
                        <div id="collapse-reputation-1" class="panel-collapse collapse" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="heading-reputation-1">
                          <div class="panel-body">
                          <p class='reg-p'>Reputation is a rough measure of how much the community trusts you, and it is earned by convincing users that you know what you are talking about. The more reputation you earn the more <a data-easing="linear" href="#privilege-faq">privileges</a> you gain and the more you can do on the site. It is set up this way because we believe in the wisdom of our users so we want them to run the site as a collective community.</p>
                          <h3>How to earn reputation</h3>
                          <p class='reg-p'>As mentioned before, the primary way to earn reputation is by convincing people that you know what you are talking about. This is primarily done by writing good problems and proofs. Votes on these posts can make you either gain or lose reputation.</p>
                          <h4>Ways to gain reputation:</h4>
                            <ul>
                              <li class='reg-item'>Problem is voted up: +5</li>
                              <li class='reg-item'>Proof is voted up: +10</li>
                              <li class='reg-item'>Comment is voted up: +2</li>
                            </ul>
                          <h4>Ways to lose reputation:</h4>
                            <ul>
                              <li class='reg-item'>Problem is voted down: -2</li>
                              <li class='reg-item'>Proof is voted down: -2</li>
                              <li class='reg-item'>Comment is voted down: -1</li>
                              <li class='reg-item'>You vote down a post: -1</li>
                            </ul>
                            <p class='reg-p'> All users start with 0 reputation and it can never drop below 0. Deleting a post will not affect the scores of the authors and people involved. When a user reverses a vote, the corresponding reputation loss or gain will be reverted as well. Note that a user cannot vote on his or her own post.</p>
                          </div>
                        </div>
                      </div><!-- / .panel -->

                      <div class="panel panel-default primary-card mb-40 faq-panel">   
                        <div class="panel-heading" style="padding: 5px 15px;" role="tab">
                          <h2 class="panel-title collapsed" role="button" data-toggle="collapse" href="#collapse-reputation-2" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapse-reputation-2" id="heading-reputation-2">
                            <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-down float-right faq-toggle-content"></span>
                            What are badges?
                          </h2>
                        </div>
                        <div id="collapse-reputation-2" class="panel-collapse collapse" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="heading-reputation-2">
                          <div class="panel-body">
                            <p class='reg-p'>Each user has a colored badge that serves as a sort of rank, and determines the level of trust he or she has earned based on his or her reputation score. This color badge appears on the user's standard card and provides a quick visual representation of the user's trustworthiness and site prestige.</p>
                            <p class='reg-p'>The following are the badges along with the corresponding reputation level needed to earn you that badge:</p>
                            <div class="row">
                              <div class="col-xs-6 col-sm-4">
                                <p class="badge-label" style="background-color: #373940;"><span class="fa fa-trophy mr-5"></span> 0</p>
                              </div>
                              <div class="col-xs-6 col-sm-4">
